03772nam a22005415i 9780822395638DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223956387 a10.1515/97808223956382doi  a(DE-B1597)554095  a(OCoLC)1202624652  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aNX650.E46 7aART0090002bisacsh04a709.05/1  aLH 610452rvk0(DE-625)rvk/94203:1 aDoyle, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHold It Against Me :bDifficulty and Emotion in Contemporary Art /cJennifer Doyle. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b45 illustrations, including 17 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- t1 Introducing Difficulty -- t2 Three Case Studies in Difficulty and the Problem of Affect -- t3 Thinking Feeling: Criticism and Emotion -- t4 Feeling Overdetermined: Identity, Emotion, and History -- tConclusion: "History Keeps Me Awake" -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Hold It Against Me, Jennifer Doyle explores the relationship between difficulty and emotion in contemporary art, treating emotion as an artist's medium. She encourages readers to examine the ways in which works of art challenge how we experience not only the artist's feelings, but our own. Discussing performance art, painting, and photography, Doyle provides new perspectives on artists including Ron Athey, Aliza Shvarts, Thomas Eakins, James Luna, Carrie Mae Weems, and David Wojnarowicz. Confronting the challenge of writing about difficult works of art, she shows how these artists work with feelings as a means to question our assumptions about identity, intimacy, and expression. They deploy the complexity of emotion to measure the weight of history, and to deepen our sense of where and how politics happens in contemporary art.Doyle explores ideologies of emotion and how emotion circulates in and around art. Throughout, she gives readers welcoming points of entry into artworks that they may at first find off-putting or confrontational. Doyle offers new insight into how the discourse of controversy serves to shut down discussion about this side of contemporary art practice, and counters with a critical language that allows the reader to accept emotional intensity in order to learn from it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395638zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395638.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles